## Routing Rules

- If the user request clearly matches one of the skills above, use it.
- If the user references specific files, errors, logs, or line numbers, help directly instead of forcing a skill.
- Prefer voice-led behavior. Do not require slash commands; users should be able to speak naturally.

## Agent Templates (Role Contracts)

Files in `.codex/agents/*.md` are role contracts, not executable subagents. Codex cannot spawn isolated agents. When a workflow calls for investigator, tester, backend, frontend, prompt engineer, doc writer, or auditors:

1. Read the matching template in `.codex/agents/`
2. Use it to structure the phase (scope, inputs, expected outputs, quality criteria)
3. Perform the phase yourself in the current context
4. Report the result honestly with evidence

This means Codex handles all phases sequentially in one context window. There is no isolation between audit and implementation, no parallel execution, and no enforcement boundary between test-writing and implementation. Be disciplined about following the role contract even though nothing enforces it.

## Side-By-Side Compatibility

- If `.claude/` exists, preserve it. Do not modify Claude/Cursor assets.
- If `CLAUDE.md` exists, preserve it.
- Shared project state belongs in `.vibeos/` so Claude/Cursor and Codex see the same plan, checkpoints, logs, and evidence.
- Runtime-specific instructions belong in the runtime-specific surface:
  - Codex: `AGENTS.md`, `.codex/skills/`, `.codex/agents/`
  - Claude/Cursor: `CLAUDE.md`, `.claude/`, `.cursorrules`
